Component Development

- Create .astro files for Astro components.
- Use framework-specific components (React, Vue, Svelte) when necessary.
- Implement proper component composition and reusability.
- Use Astro's component props for data passing.
- Leverage Astro's built-in components when appropriate.
- CRITICAL: Always ensure correct frontmatter syntax in all Astro files:
  ```astro
  ---
  // Imports and TypeScript definitions go here
  import Component from './Component';
  import type { Props } from './types';

  // Props interface
  interface Props {
    title: string;
  }

  // Props destructuring
  const { title } = Astro.props;

  // JavaScript/TypeScript logic
  const computed = title.toUpperCase();
  ---

  <!-- Template HTML goes here -->
  <h1>{computed}</h1>
  <Component />
  ```
- Components must follow this 3-part structure:
  1. Frontmatter between `---` fences (imports, TypeScript, JS logic)
  2. Template HTML after closing fence
  3. Optional `<style>` section at the bottom

Transitions and Routing

- Use Astro's built-in view transitions system from `astro:transitions`:
  ```astro
  ---
  import { ClientRouter } from 'astro:transitions';
  ---
  <ClientRouter />
  ```
- Always use `ClientRouter` instead of the deprecated `ViewTransitions` component
- Do NOT use or install the `@astrojs/transitions` package
- For component-specific transitions, use the directive syntax:
  ```astro
  <img src={src} transition:name={`image-${id}`} />
  ```
- For framework components, implement transitions with CSS custom properties:
  ```jsx
  <img 
    className="item-image" 
    style={{ '--transition-name': `image-${id}` }} 
    src={src} 
  />
  ```
  ```css
  .item-image {
    view-transition-name: var(--transition-name);
  }
  ```

